June lows near 183.15, yet the pace of that recovery has slowed materially as price approaches overhead supply, leaving the desk's bias firmly neutral.\n\nThe structure story on the daily timeframe is one of a pair of competing forces. From the 24 June trough, EUR/JPY carved out a sequence of higher lows and, latterly, higher closes, culminating in yesterday's session that tagged 186.03 before pulling back to settle just below 185.93. That intraday high brought price squarely into contact with the prior reaction zone sitting at 185.97, a level that has now registered three distinct touches across recent weeks and has consistently capped upside momentum. Above that sits a more defined structure resistance band around 186.22, which has twice turned price lower and would represent the next meaningful ceiling should the 185.97 area give way. On the downside, the desk notes a structure support shelf at 185.83, which has held on two tests and is now acting as the immediate floor. A far deeper prior reaction zone at 182.07 remains the broader anchor should sentiment shift materially in favour of the yen.\n\nThe H1 read reinforces the neutral stance. Since the early-morning push to 186.03, the cross has spent the bulk of the session oscillating within an exceptionally tight band between roughly 185.82 and 186.00. Candle bodies are compressed and there is no clear directional impetus on the hourly chart. Price is essentially pinned between the structure support at 185.83 and the prior reaction zone at 185.97, and neither side has mustered the conviction to break free. This kind of consolidation following a multi-day advance is consistent with either a continuation pause or a distribution phase \u2014 the chart alone cannot distinguish between the two at this juncture.\n\nToday's calendar is light for EUR/JPY. The Italian Trade Balance and the broader Eurozone Trade Balance, both due at 05:00 UTC, carry low impact ratings and are unlikely to generate meaningful volatility in isolation. Absent a significant surprise, these releases should not materially alter the technical picture, and the cross may remain range-bound through the European morning.\n\nWhat would change the read? A sustained hourly close above the 185.97 prior reaction zone, ideally with follow-through toward 186.22, would begin to shift the picture in a more constructive direction. Conversely, a clean break and close beneath the 185.83 structure support on the H1 chart would suggest the recovery from late June is stalling, opening the door to a retest of the 184.50\u2013184.80 area that capped multiple sessions earlier this month. Until either scenario materialises, the cross looks content to consolidate.\n\nThis is editorial analysis, not financial advice. Trading involves substantial risk of loss.", "sample": false}